From fa2c6453ae5dad8ef6d020333b98ff55afa12a76 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: vllm-shim <vllm-shim@local>
Date: Thu, 1 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 9/9] debug(sglang): per-layer post-MoE dump for EP vs non-EP
 head-to-head

Static analysis of the K2.6 MoRI EP gibberish has gone as far as it can.
Mask, remap, weight slots, dispatch routing, and combine all align under
_remap_topk_for_deepep (topk.py:1017-1058): the byte-identical DP4/5/6
row 0 outputs we saw in the EP-DUMP are the home-rank shared-expert path
behaving correctly, not a bug. But the gibberish symptom is real (Test 2
confirmed non-EP is coherent at 21 tok/s with this same image), so the
divergence must live somewhere our static read missed.

Add a head-to-head probe. VLLM_SHIM_MOE_POST_DUMP=N logs the first N
post-MoE hidden states per (layer_id, mode) pair where mode is "ep" or
"nonep". Two call sites land at the semantic same point:

  MoriEPMoE.forward (post-combine, pre-return)
    -> maybe_dump_post_moe(layer_id, "ep", hidden_states[:num_token])

  QuarkW4A4MXFp4MoE.apply_weights (post-triton_mxfp4_moe, non-EP path)
    -> maybe_dump_post_moe(layer.layer_id, "nonep", output)

Both paths certifiedly call the same triton_mxfp4_moe function (the
non-EP fallback at quark_w4a4_mxfp4_moe.py:241 with no expert_mask /
num_local_tokens, so ep_mode=False inside). So "non-EP works" certifies
the kernel under dense input; the dump tells us whether the EP-mode
output of the same kernel + combine drifts from the dense reference.

Each line carries abs_mean, abs_max, l2, and a first-row signature.
Operator runs the same prompt once in each mode and joins on
(layer_id, call). Layer 0 should match within bf16 noise; the first
layer that doesn't is where the EP path starts diverging from the
math non-EP performs. That localizes the bug from "somewhere in 60
MoE layers" to "in or before layer N".

Disabled by default; no overhead when VLLM_SHIM_MOE_POST_DUMP=0.
